  "voiceover": "Is the universe fine-tuned for life? Here's the part that isn't controversial. The fundamental constants of physics — the force of gravity, the balance of the forces, the expansion rate of the cosmos — sit inside an astonishingly narrow range that permits life. Move many of them by a hair and there are no stars, no planets, no chemistry, no us. Even atheist physicists concede the data. The debate is only over what explains it. There are three options: physical necessity, chance, or design. Necessity has no evidence that the constants had to be this way. Chance has to reach for an unobserved multiverse — countless unseen universes — just to make our odds look less lonely. Design remains a serious, simpler candidate. The fine-tuning is the fact. Design is the inference — contested, but honest. As the psalmist wrote long before the physics: the heavens declare the glory of God.",
